IDENTIFY the bellies of the three muscles of the posterior deep
e.g. the great toe is on the MEDIAL side of the foot, but the flexor hallucis longus originates on the LATERAL side of the leg.

On the medial side of the leg, identify the muscle belly of the flexor digitorum longus. In the diagram, note that in the foot it forms four tendons that cross the plantar aspect of the lateral four toes. Contraction of the flexor digitorum longus curls the toes under, i.e. it is a flexor of the lateral four toes, as its name suggests. It is important in the push-off phase of the gait cycle.  
On the lateral side of the leg, identify the muscle belly of the flexor hallucis longus. In the diagram, follow the tendons of the flexor hallucis longus across the plantar aspect of the great toe. Contraction of the flexor hallucis longus curls the great toe under, i.e. it is a flexor of the great toe, as its name suggests. This muscle is important in propelling us forward during the gait cycle and upward when we jump.
Notice that the positions of these muscle bellies are on opposite sides of the limb with respect to their points of insertion     . This necessitates that their tendons cross in the sole of the foot as illustrated in the diagram. 
Identify the intermediate muscle, the tibialis posterior, TP. In the diagram, follow the tendon of the TP to the medial aspect of the foot. When the muscle contracts, it pulls up on the medial aspect of the foot to cause inversion. It is also important in supporting the medial longitudinal arch of the foot.
